00:04:02.690 --> 00:04:08.030
or relics, giving to the poor, or the sacraments,
or any action that a person can take. We can’t

00:04:08.030 --> 00:04:13.360
ever be good enough, through our actions,
to merit salvation. We can only have faith.

00:04:13.360 --> 00:04:16.900
In Latin, sola fide, only faith.
Thanks, Thought Bubble.

00:04:16.900 --> 00:04:21.709
So, Martin Luther’s new interpretation of
“sola fide” grew into a full-scale conflict

00:04:21.709 --> 00:04:26.589
with the Catholic Church when a friar named
John Tetzel came to Wittenberg, selling indulgences.

00:04:26.589 --> 00:04:30.520
An indulgence was a donation to the church
that came with a promise from the pope to

00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:35.490
reduce a sinner’s time in purgatory. Like,
to quote from an indulgence that Friar Tetzel

00:04:35.490 --> 00:04:42.020
sold, “[I] replace thee in the state of innocence and
purity in which thou wert at the hour of thy baptism."

00:04:42.020 --> 00:04:45.820
Luther felt like that that wasn’t the sort of thing that, you know, should be for sale.

00:04:45.820 --> 00:04:49.300
The price of this whole-life complete-forgiveness-of-any-horrible-sin

00:04:49.300 --> 00:04:53.540
certificate, by the way, was three marks,
probably about half a year’s wages for a

00:04:53.540 --> 00:04:55.639
laborer.
So, Luther didn’t like seeing his parishioners

00:04:55.639 --> 00:05:00.369
handing over money they didn’t have for
a scrap of paper that he believed to be meaningless,

00:05:00.369 --> 00:05:06.559
so in response, he wrote 95 Theses against
indulgences, and then dramatically nailed

00:05:06.559 --> 00:05:12.430
them to the Church door, for all to see on
October 31, 1517—or else he mailed them

00:05:12.430 --> 00:05:15.180
to the archbishop, or possibly both. We don’t
actually know.

00:05:15.180 --> 00:05:19.059
This led to a series of debates with other
men of the cloth, during which Luther’s

00:05:19.059 --> 00:05:23.939
positions became increasingly radical. Starting
from the statement that Christians were saved

00:05:23.939 --> 00:05:28.909
only through faith and the grace of God, for instance,
Luther then upped the ante, saying that the Church’s

00:05:28.909 --> 00:05:34.909
rituals didn't have the power to save souls.
And then he argued that far from being infallible,

00:05:34.909 --> 00:05:37.649
the church, and the pope made errors all the
time.

00:05:37.649 --> 00:05:41.839
That was a pretty bold thing to say, and then
it got even more dramatic when Luther ultimately

00:05:41.839 --> 00:05:46.710
denied that the church and the officers of
it had any spiritual powers.

00:05:46.710 --> 00:05:50.619
He said that the priesthood was a human invention;
and that individual Christians didn’t even

00:05:50.619 --> 00:05:54.990
need priests to receive the grace of God.
Instead, Luther described a “priesthood

00:05:54.990 --> 00:05:58.889
of all believers.”
So this had gone from a call for reforming

00:05:58.889 --> 00:06:04.679
indulgences to, to a revolution. So in
1521, Luther was called to defend his ideas

00:06:04.679 --> 00:06:09.939
before the Holy Roman Emperor, Charles V,
at the Imperial Diet of Worms. Or in German,

00:06:09.939 --> 00:06:12.569
Worms.
Also, let me say retroactively, now that everyone

00:06:12.569 --> 00:06:15.700
has commented on my poor German pronunciation,
Wittenberg.

00:06:15.700 --> 00:06:20.240
Emperor Charles famously said, “A single
friar who goes counter to all Christianity

00:06:20.240 --> 00:06:25.080
for a thousand years must be wrong.”
To which Luther was like, “stop flapping

00:06:25.080 --> 00:06:28.960
that hideous Hapsburg jaw of yours.”
But there was something to what Charles was

00:06:28.960 --> 00:06:33.800
saying, right? Because plenty of radical friars
had criticized the church’s abuses and hypocrisies

00:06:33.800 --> 00:06:39.449
over the years; why would Luther prove influential?
Well, one reason was the printing press.

00:06:39.449 --> 00:06:43.520
Now, most people in Europe at the time couldn’t
read, but a lot of people could, including,

00:06:43.520 --> 00:06:48.759
of course a lot of priests. And over two thousand
editions of Luther’s writings appeared between

00:06:48.759 --> 00:06:52.579
1517 and 1526.
And his ideas also appeared in pamphlets,

00:06:52.580 --> 00:06:57.620
and posters, and cartoons that were seen and
read aloud, reaching millions of readers and

00:06:57.620 --> 00:07:00.219
listeners,
In short, Luther’s ideas were all over,

00:07:00.219 --> 00:07:05.610
like, the Tumblr of the day, which was a town
crier and broadsides nailed to doors.

00:07:05.610 --> 00:07:09.529
And it caused quite a stir, especially the part
about, like, the Pope being the Anti-Christ

00:07:09.529 --> 00:07:12.009
sent by the devil. Like I said, it got pretty
radical.

00:07:12.009 --> 00:07:16.729
But maybe the most revolutionary of Luther’s
